<h3>Etymology</h3>

<p>
The name <strong>Chrysanthemum</strong> comes from Greek meaning “gold flower.”
</p>

<h2>Ecology</h2>

<p>
Mums provide late-season nectar for pollinators and thrive in temperate climates with cool autumn temperatures.
</p>

<h3>Diseases and pests</h3>

<ul>
<li>Aphids on buds</li>
<li>Leaf miners in foliage</li>
<li>Powdery mildew in humid conditions</li>
<li>Spider mites in dry weather</li>
</ul>

<h2>Cultivation</h2>

<p>
Chrysanthemums are widely cultivated for ornamental and seasonal autumn displays.
</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Light:</strong> Full sun</li>
<li><strong>Soil:</strong> Well-drained, fertile soil</li>
<li><strong>Water:</strong> Moderate</li>
<li><strong>Planting:</strong> Cuttings or divisions</li>
<li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> Pinch back for bushier growth</li>
</ul>

<h2>Mums in culture</h2>

<p>
Chrysanthemums symbolize longevity, joy, and remembrance and are especially important in Asian and European traditions.
</p>

